Build, test, and publish release binaries in CI

Replace the separate build-and-release workflow with a single CI
workflow that runs the test suite the way local development does:
inside the .devcontainer image, under sysbox, with systemd and nested
containers. The linux jobs install sysbox and call ci/run-pipeline.sh,
which builds the image, boots it, checks out the commit under test, and
runs cargo pipeline --release. Keeping the sequence in a script keeps
the workflow thin and lets the same steps run locally.

The commit under test is fetched straight from its origin over the
network (REPO_URL/COMMIT) rather than bind-mounted, so a fork's own
repo works by pointing REPO_URL at it. The devcontainer's baked-in
clone with its prebuilt target/ is preserved for incremental builds.
The base image is already pinned by digest in the Dockerfile.

The published binaries are the ones the tests ran against, not a
separate build: cargo pipeline --release builds and tests the optimized
rumpel binary (the --release flag threads through to xtest, which
builds the tests and the binary under test with --release), and
run-pipeline.sh copies that binary out of the container for the release
job to attach to the GitHub release on tags. macos is build-only
because its runners have no docker daemon for the pod tests. Jobs are
flat, not a matrix, so each platform shows up on its own in the checks
UI.

Getting the LLM replay cache to hit under CI's strict offline mode
required making the agents deterministic. Claude decides some behavior
at runtime rather than from the image: it fetches Statsig feature gates
keyed on a random per-run anonymousId, and those gates add a "ttl"
prompt-cache hint and inject a random available-skills reminder into
tool results, so the same devcontainer image behaved differently in CI
than locally. The claude tests set
CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC (no gate fetch) and
CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_THINKING (thinking signatures are fresh every
generation) in the devcontainer remoteEnv. Two residual, non-Claude
sources are normalized out of the cache key: the random port the pod
git server binds (which leaks into git remote -v tool output) and
grok's available-skills reminder (listed in a nondeterministic on-disk
order); grok's cache is re-recorded for the new key.
